        <title type="html"><![CDATA[Memory network 4 -- What kind of struct should we use ?]]></title>
        <id>https://matrixowl.github.io/post/dynamic-graph-4-what-kind-of-struct-should-we-use/</id>
        <link href="https://matrixowl.github.io/post/dynamic-graph-4-what-kind-of-struct-should-we-use/">
        </link>
        <updated>2020-08-10T09:09:44.000Z</updated>
        <content type="html"><![CDATA[<p>If you want to make a huge building, the first thing we have to do is know what this building will look like. You can't fucking build a building look like both tiananmen and wiltehouse. Or maybe you can but it will like a fucking strange monster.<br>
So, this article will discussion about the struct of our dynamic network.<br>
I think the network can simple divid into three part:</p>
<ol>
<li>The input block</li>
<li>The memory block</li>
<li>The output block<br>
As for the type of neuron I said in the previous article, we temporary confirm there will only one variety. Becouse make the neuron different is bad of the expandability.<br>
About the three block of our network:</li>
<li>-- The input block<br>
This block will used to deal with the diffierent kinds of data, extract there feature, than put them(the feature) into memory block to learn. And this part will have a dynamic connect with the memory block, when a node of memory block have a high &quot;vitality&quot;, it will completely not connect with input block.</li>
<li>-- The memory block<br>
This block is the main part of our network, the &quot;dynamic&quot; mostly means this block have a regular change. Becouse this part is maintain the memory function of network, just like the cerebral cortex(Just maybe, I have to say I'm not a good biology student).</li>
<li>-- The output block<br>
This block is just like the traditional neuron network, but it can add new node of new class.</li>
</ol>
<p>This article will just a simple intorduction of the dynamic network sturcture, we will make a detailed discussion in another article.<br>
And so far, the problem in the second article all have a general outline.</p>
]]></content>
    </entry>
